WEBVTT

00:14.056 --> 00:16.225
♪ theme song playing ♪

00:16.225 --> 00:19.228
‐ ♪ It's time for Animaniacs! ♪

00:19.853 --> 00:22.064
♪ And we're zany to the max ♪

00:22.689 --> 00:24.399
♪ So just sit back and relax ♪

00:24.399 --> 00:25.984
♪ You'll laugh till you collapse ♪

00:25.984 --> 00:27.986
♪ We're Animaniacs! ♪

00:28.529 --> 00:31.698
‐ ♪ Come join the Warner Brothers ♪
‐ ♪ And the Warner Sister Dot ♪

00:31.698 --> 00:34.701
♪ Just for fun, we run around
the Warner movie lot ♪

00:34.701 --> 00:37.329
♪ They lock us in the tower
whenever we get caught ♪

00:37.329 --> 00:40.332
♪ But we break loose and then vamoose
and now you know the plot ♪

00:40.332 --> 00:42.334
♪ We're Animaniacs ♪

00:42.876 --> 00:45.754
♪ Dot has wit and Yakko yaks ♪

00:45.754 --> 00:47.297
♪ Wakko packs away the snacks ♪

00:47.297 --> 00:49.007
♪ Our careers have made comebacks ♪

00:49.007 --> 00:50.884
♪ We're Animaniacs! ♪

00:51.635 --> 00:54.638
♪ Meet Pinky and the Brain
who want to rule the universe ♪

00:54.638 --> 00:57.391
♪ A brand new cast who tested well
in focus group research ♪

00:57.391 --> 00:59.142
♪ Gender balanced, pronoun neutral ♪

00:59.142 --> 01:00.561
♪ And ethnically diverse ♪

01:00.561 --> 01:03.397
♪ The trolls will say we're so passé,
but we did meta first ♪

01:03.397 --> 01:05.899
♪ We're Animaniacs ♪

01:05.899 --> 01:08.986
♪ You should see our new contracts ♪

01:08.986 --> 01:11.989
♪ We're zany to the max,
there's baloney in our slacks ♪

01:11.989 --> 01:14.950
♪ We're animan‐ey, totally insane‐y ♪

01:14.950 --> 01:16.577
‐ ♪ Mirage arcane‐y ♪

01:16.577 --> 01:20.080
‐ ♪ Animaniacs! Those are the facts ♪

01:23.125 --> 01:25.919
♪

01:28.422 --> 01:31.425
♪

01:34.136 --> 01:36.263
[shaking, clattering]

01:36.263 --> 01:37.931
‐ Ah! Snake eyes!

01:38.515 --> 01:40.559
‐ Yeah, that means you
married your prom date

01:40.559 --> 01:42.895
and you both shop for
jeans at the grocery store.

01:42.895 --> 01:44.646
‐ But I never got to live abroad!

01:44.646 --> 01:46.690
Or try stand‐up comedy!

01:46.690 --> 01:48.692
‐ And you never will.

01:48.692 --> 01:50.569
‐ That's why they call it settling!

01:50.569 --> 01:51.612
[rumbling]

01:51.612 --> 01:53.071
[screaming]
[crashing]

01:54.031 --> 01:56.867
♪ intimidating music ♪

01:56.867 --> 01:59.119
[whirring]

01:59.119 --> 02:01.121
[clicking]

02:02.539 --> 02:03.999
[beeping]

02:06.543 --> 02:08.170
[alien noises]

02:08.170 --> 02:11.882
‐ You know, this would be scarier
if we hadn't already done aliens...

02:11.882 --> 02:13.717
twice this season.

02:13.717 --> 02:14.718
[beep]

02:14.718 --> 02:16.428
‐ Sorry about that.

02:16.428 --> 02:18.222
Are you the one they call...

02:18.222 --> 02:19.431
The Yak?

02:19.431 --> 02:22.351
‐ It's Yakk‐O.
And it depends who's asking,

02:22.351 --> 02:24.686
four plus four plus four... eyes.

02:24.686 --> 02:27.731
‐ We hear you are best at
condensing complex information

02:27.731 --> 02:29.191
into catchy jingles.

02:29.191 --> 02:32.528
‐ Well, maybe not the best...

02:32.528 --> 02:34.863
But yeah, objectively the best.
You heard right.

02:34.863 --> 02:38.450
‐ What is everything about Earth? Please.

02:38.450 --> 02:40.118
‐ Everything about Earth!?

02:40.118 --> 02:41.453
♪

02:41.453 --> 02:43.205
Uh...

02:43.205 --> 02:44.873
[sighs] Okay.

02:44.873 --> 02:46.708
Well, I'm gonna need a 92‐piece orchestra

02:46.708 --> 02:48.919
and a lukewarm green tea
with lemon and honey.

02:49.378 --> 02:50.379
[snap]

02:50.379 --> 02:51.421
[whirring, zap]

02:56.176 --> 02:57.636
I said luke warm!

02:57.636 --> 02:59.096
Luke!
[snap]

02:59.096 --> 03:00.138
[zap]

03:00.931 --> 03:01.932
That's more like it.

03:02.307 --> 03:04.685
Maestro, if you please.

03:05.769 --> 03:09.189
♪ At first there was nothingness,
then some unknown process ♪

03:09.189 --> 03:11.191
♪ Lead to a great big explosion ♪

03:11.191 --> 03:13.443
♪ The universe grew
from a subatomic stew ♪

03:13.443 --> 03:15.696
♪ Of quarks, gluons, plasmas, and bosons ♪

03:15.696 --> 03:17.990
♪ Then gas and dust settled
on hot cores of metal ♪

03:17.990 --> 03:20.284
♪ And one of these
cores was called Earth ♪

03:20.284 --> 03:22.244
♪ It was covered with goop,
a primordial soup ♪

03:22.244 --> 03:24.705
♪ From which all of Earth's
life was then birthed ♪

03:24.705 --> 03:26.999
♪ At first, single cells,
some swam or grew shells ♪

03:26.999 --> 03:29.126
♪ Still others evolved to hunt prey ♪

03:29.126 --> 03:31.461
♪ Some hid in the sand,
some crawled onto land ♪

03:31.461 --> 03:34.756
♪ So life, well, life found a way... ♪

03:34.756 --> 03:36.758
‐ Uh, we already did this bit.

03:36.758 --> 03:38.886
Uh huh, in the pilot. Mm‐hmm.

03:40.137 --> 03:43.140
‐ ♪ There were mosses and gymnosperms,
seven‐foot‐long earthworms ♪

03:43.140 --> 03:45.017
♪ Huge dragonflies ruled the sky ♪

03:45.017 --> 03:47.060
♪ Amphibians, cephalopods,
pedallers both bi‐ and quad‐ ♪

03:47.060 --> 03:49.021
♪ Reptiles started to fly ♪

03:49.021 --> 03:51.023
♪ We had lizards grow big and small,
mammals not big at all ♪

03:51.023 --> 03:53.066
♪ Sharks were the size of a house ♪

03:53.066 --> 03:55.277
♪ Then, one little meteor
killed all the dinosaurs ♪

03:55.277 --> 03:56.820
♪ So, we evolved from a mouse ♪

03:56.820 --> 03:58.822
♪ 8,000 BC, Creation Theory ♪

03:58.822 --> 04:00.741
♪ Would dictate the song
should start here ♪

04:00.741 --> 04:02.659
♪ Though most of our herd
agree it's absurd ♪

04:02.659 --> 04:06.538
♪ Some teach it in place
of Shakespeare... ♪

04:06.997 --> 04:09.166
♪ Let's skip evolution,
there're two revolutions ♪

04:09.166 --> 04:11.335
♪ Agriculture took us to towns ♪

04:11.335 --> 04:13.253
♪ Humans learned to grow wheat,
got all fat, loved to eat ♪

04:13.253 --> 04:14.963
♪ Stopped walking and just settled down ♪

04:14.963 --> 04:16.840
♪ Industrial next, its major effect ♪

04:16.840 --> 04:18.383
♪ To take us from towns to the city ♪

04:18.383 --> 04:20.844
♪ We mined coals and built trains,
machines plowed our grains ♪

04:20.844 --> 04:22.221
♪ And we treated the workers real shi‐‐ ♪

04:22.221 --> 04:24.264
‐ How many more of your Earth
seconds is this going to take?

04:24.264 --> 04:26.183
‐ Well‐timed interruption.
Almost there, I promise!

04:26.183 --> 04:28.018
♪ We recorded some tunes,
put a man on the moon ♪

04:28.018 --> 04:30.020
♪ Fought more wars
than we care to recount ♪

04:30.020 --> 04:31.605
♪ Sent the Phoenix to Mars,
built electric cars ♪

04:31.605 --> 04:33.357
♪ And polluted a shocking amount ♪

04:33.357 --> 04:35.359
♪ Skipping to now,
we survived, not sure how ♪

04:35.359 --> 04:37.611
♪ It's getting real hard to keep track ♪

04:37.611 --> 04:38.737
[inhales deeply]

04:38.737 --> 04:40.697
♪ There's Wikipedia, smartphones,
tablets, unmanned drones ♪

04:40.697 --> 04:42.449
♪ Pick your own genomes,
ride‐sharing, sheep clones ♪

04:42.449 --> 04:44.076
♪ Earthquakes and cyclones,
valleys of Silicone ♪

04:44.076 --> 04:45.953
♪ Gluten‐free vegan scones,
temperature milestones ♪

04:45.953 --> 04:47.913
♪ Keystones and sword thrones,
high‐interest payday loans ♪

04:47.913 --> 04:50.082
♪ Cyclists' testosterone,
and everything Musk owns ♪

04:50.082 --> 04:53.919
♪ But at least now us Warners are ♪

04:53.919 --> 04:57.464
♪ Back! ♪

04:57.965 --> 04:59.967
We are back, baby!

05:00.801 --> 05:02.469
♪

05:02.469 --> 05:04.304
[clapping]

05:04.304 --> 05:08.016
‐ You have been most helpful, The Yak.

05:08.016 --> 05:10.102
‐ Yes. While we absorb the essence

05:10.102 --> 05:12.062
of all species on your planet,

05:12.062 --> 05:13.605
we will ensure your carbon atoms

05:13.605 --> 05:15.232
are re‐purposed for only

05:15.232 --> 05:17.734
the highest quality nutrient paste.

05:17.734 --> 05:19.403
[slurping]

05:19.403 --> 05:22.155
♪

05:24.950 --> 05:26.410
‐ Joke's on them!

05:26.410 --> 05:28.495
We aren't even a species!

05:32.416 --> 05:34.501
NARRATOR: CEO Michael Benton.
[applause]

05:34.501 --> 05:36.295
Silicon Valley venture capitalist,

05:36.295 --> 05:37.713
egomaniac,

05:37.713 --> 05:39.548
searching for everlasting life.

05:42.092 --> 05:45.637
Then, a freak accident transforms
his biological makeup...

05:45.637 --> 05:48.015
[fizzling, boom]

05:48.015 --> 05:50.684
...turning him into an angry gnome.

05:51.310 --> 05:52.561
[yelling]

05:52.561 --> 05:54.438
The creature is driven by rage...

05:54.438 --> 05:55.314
[yelling]

05:55.314 --> 05:57.482
...and must now live in people's mouths...

05:58.400 --> 06:01.278
‐ Who do you think you are,
bullying somebody around!?

06:01.278 --> 06:04.573
NARRATOR: ...and speak for them when
they cannot speak for themselves.

06:05.115 --> 06:07.326
‐ You're just waiting around
for the clock to tick!

06:07.326 --> 06:09.077
[car rumbling]

06:10.037 --> 06:11.413
♪

06:11.413 --> 06:12.372
[roar]

06:15.167 --> 06:18.545
NARRATOR: He is
The Incredible Gnome In People's Mouths.

06:21.882 --> 06:24.843
♪

06:24.843 --> 06:26.345
‐ Oh... What?

06:26.345 --> 06:29.181
Where's my pudding?
[slurping]

06:29.181 --> 06:32.559
Hey! Uh... That's my pudding!

06:32.559 --> 06:35.521
‐ I don't see your name on it.
Besides, it's just butterscotch.

06:35.521 --> 06:37.022
You probably wouldn't even like it.

06:37.022 --> 06:40.275
Don't want you getting cavities.
Bad for your teeth.

06:40.275 --> 06:43.570
‐ Hey! Uh... Oh...

06:43.570 --> 06:45.697
[gagging, grunting]

06:45.697 --> 06:47.699
‐ Hey! Get your hands off that pudding!

06:48.325 --> 06:49.785
[screaming]

06:50.827 --> 06:53.914
Don't you know how to respect
your elders and their puddings?

06:53.914 --> 06:56.667
Lemme talk to your supervisor!

06:56.667 --> 06:57.835
♪

06:57.835 --> 07:00.546
‐ Now, I'm sure if we just talk calmly

07:00.546 --> 07:02.130
about what happened.

07:02.130 --> 07:04.842
‐ The time for calm
talking has passed, sister!

07:04.842 --> 07:07.177
She boosted that butterscotch
right out from under

07:07.177 --> 07:10.222
that baby boy's booger box!
‐ I'm sorry!

07:10.222 --> 07:13.100
I have low blood sugar,
and I don't get a lunch break.

07:13.100 --> 07:16.103
So, I get irritable.
‐ You're irritable!?

07:16.103 --> 07:17.729
I'm stuck in this old man's mouth,

07:17.729 --> 07:20.858
and he quit brushing in 1972!

07:20.858 --> 07:23.902
I know your job is hard,
but you can't lash out

07:23.902 --> 07:27.239
by pilfering pudding! And you...

07:27.239 --> 07:30.951
I wonder how the governor
would feel about your blatant disregard

07:30.951 --> 07:34.162
of the revised California labor laws,

07:34.162 --> 07:37.082
section 22 G, requiring lunch breaks

07:37.082 --> 07:40.878
for all employees whose
shifts exceed seven hours!

07:40.878 --> 07:43.422
‐ Oh, I‐I'm sure we can resolve this.

07:45.215 --> 07:47.759
♪

07:47.759 --> 07:50.804
‐ Someone stole all the corner pieces!

07:50.804 --> 07:54.433
‐ Hold on one minute, Mrs. Miller.
I'm on my lunch break.

07:55.893 --> 07:58.312
[slurp]
[grunting]

07:58.312 --> 07:59.313
‐ You're welcome!

07:59.730 --> 08:01.857
[laughing]
‐ Help!

08:01.857 --> 08:03.567
[rumbling]
[grunts]

08:03.567 --> 08:05.319
‐ Hm!
[revving]

08:05.319 --> 08:07.196
[tire screech]
[laughing]

08:07.196 --> 08:09.823
‐ I wonder where he'll go next.

08:09.823 --> 08:12.326
‐ I suppose wherever
there's a helpless person

08:12.326 --> 08:14.912
whose problems can be
solved by violent screaming

08:14.912 --> 08:16.872
and reckless intimidation.

08:16.872 --> 08:20.876
♪

08:27.966 --> 08:29.134
[thunder]

08:29.134 --> 08:32.137
♪ Pinky & The Brain theme ♪

08:33.180 --> 08:34.890
‐ Gee, Brain,
what do you wanna do tonight?

08:35.766 --> 08:38.519
‐ The same thing we do every night, Pinky.

08:38.519 --> 08:41.980
Try to take over the world!
[thunder]

08:41.980 --> 08:44.066
♪

08:44.066 --> 08:46.026
‐ ♪ They're Pinky and the Brain ♪

08:46.026 --> 08:48.195
♪ Yes, Pinky and the Brain ♪

08:48.195 --> 08:50.072
♪ One is a genius ♪

08:50.072 --> 08:52.032
♪ The other's insane ♪

08:52.032 --> 08:54.034
♪ They're laboratory mice ♪

08:54.034 --> 08:56.036
♪ Their genes have been spliced ♪

08:56.036 --> 08:58.664
♪ They're dinky,
they're Pinky and the Brain ♪

08:58.664 --> 09:00.666
♪ Brain, Brain, Brain, Brain ♪

09:07.339 --> 09:10.342
♪

09:11.802 --> 09:14.805
♪

09:14.805 --> 09:15.806
[typing, beeping]

09:15.806 --> 09:17.140
‐ Oh. [grunts]

09:17.140 --> 09:19.810
How much longer do
I have to hold this, Brain?

09:19.810 --> 09:22.604
[grunts] It's almost
a quarter to 11:00! [gasps]

09:22.604 --> 09:24.690
It's way past my lunchtime already.

09:24.690 --> 09:25.691
[groans]

09:25.691 --> 09:27.734
‐ Patience, Pinky. I am attempting

09:27.734 --> 09:30.237
to hack into the control
unit for this traffic light.

09:30.237 --> 09:33.115
‐ Oh! Are we going to throw
a traffic light party?

09:33.115 --> 09:35.158
Well, I shall have to
wear yellow because...

09:35.158 --> 09:36.451
[typing, beeping]

09:36.451 --> 09:39.538
It's complicated.
‐ We have no time to carouse, Pinky.

09:39.538 --> 09:42.666
I'm working on a scheme to triple
the length of every red light

09:42.666 --> 09:46.128
on Earth, causing mankind
to go insane with road rage,

09:46.128 --> 09:49.840
paving the way for me to seize control
of a world torn asunder!

09:49.840 --> 09:50.841
[beep]
Ha!

09:50.841 --> 09:52.384
[buzz]
[tires screech]

09:52.384 --> 09:54.052
[cars honking]
‐ Gah!

09:54.052 --> 09:55.721
Come on!
[honking]

09:55.721 --> 09:57.681
I'm late for my anger management class!

09:57.681 --> 10:00.434
[cars honking]

10:00.767 --> 10:02.811
‐ Ha! You see? It's working!

10:02.811 --> 10:04.188
[bike approaching, brakes squeal]

10:04.188 --> 10:06.148
♪

10:06.148 --> 10:07.191
[coughing]

10:07.191 --> 10:09.818
Pinky! [cough]
Are you pondering what I'm pondering?

10:10.360 --> 10:12.154
‐ [woozy]: I think so, Brain,

10:12.154 --> 10:13.989
but if the house is pickles,

10:13.989 --> 10:16.366
who would horse the hose down?

10:16.366 --> 10:19.661
Ah! I've got you by the gills now,
Wet Gregory!

10:20.787 --> 10:21.914
♪

10:21.914 --> 10:22.414
[gasps]

10:24.708 --> 10:27.252
♪

10:27.252 --> 10:29.338
MAN:
Fine weather we're having.

10:29.338 --> 10:31.423
‐ Fine weather we're having.
‐ Fine weather we're having.

10:31.423 --> 10:32.633
‐ Fine weather we're having.

10:34.051 --> 10:36.345
[gasps]
[bicycle clicking]

10:36.345 --> 10:39.181
‐ Pinky, wake up. We've been mouse‐napped.

10:39.181 --> 10:42.893
‐ Well, I've was been napping,
until you waked me up.

10:42.893 --> 10:45.437
‐ We must escape this
horrendous place at once.

10:45.437 --> 10:48.565
Looks like Wes Anderson had
a seizure at Brooks Brothers.

10:48.565 --> 10:49.983
♪

10:49.983 --> 10:52.611
‐ Sorry. There's no way out.

10:52.611 --> 10:54.363
Except by ferry,

10:54.363 --> 10:57.449
but that won't come
until tomorrow at 8:30 AM.

10:57.824 --> 11:00.244
It's always a pleasure to meet

11:00.244 --> 11:01.954
two fellow super‐villains.

11:02.579 --> 11:05.582
I am Dr. Doppler.

11:05.582 --> 11:08.877
‐ Fellow super‐villains?
You think I'm super?

11:08.877 --> 11:11.171
Well, I'm flattered, honestly, but...

11:11.171 --> 11:13.924
No, no. I want answers, Doppler.

11:13.924 --> 11:16.343
Where have you brought us?
‐ Why, this

11:16.343 --> 11:18.762
is Dopplerville!

11:18.762 --> 11:22.474
A super‐duper
super‐villain island retreat,

11:22.474 --> 11:25.686
where my hench‐people and hench‐sheeple

11:25.686 --> 11:29.022
can live and work together
to harness the weather

11:29.022 --> 11:31.942
and create global chaos!

11:31.942 --> 11:33.193
[zap]

11:33.193 --> 11:36.071
[evil laugh]

11:36.071 --> 11:38.323
Why? Do you not have

11:38.323 --> 11:41.201
a super‐duper super‐villain
island retreat?

11:41.201 --> 11:44.454
‐ Um, of course I do.
‐ [laughs] No, you don't!

11:44.454 --> 11:45.914
‐ Well, I have a lab. Though,

11:45.914 --> 11:48.584
I guess it's not technically my lab.

11:48.584 --> 11:50.210
‐ It's a cage!

11:50.210 --> 11:53.505
‐ It's more of a rental space,
but it keeps overhead low.

11:53.505 --> 11:55.549
‐ It's got a major rodent problem!

11:55.549 --> 11:57.718
[grunts]
DOPPLER: I see.

11:57.718 --> 12:01.680
Well, if everything goes
according to my plan,

12:01.680 --> 12:06.602
you'll be out of that
rusty rat trap faster than
a winter cold front.

12:06.602 --> 12:11.523
Now then, why don't we let
your weary selves sit a bit?
‐ Ooh!

12:11.523 --> 12:13.859
I haven't seen so much food
since a second ago

12:13.859 --> 12:16.695
when I saw all this food
for the first time! [laughs]

12:16.695 --> 12:18.363
Do you mind if I have some?

12:18.363 --> 12:20.032
I still haven't had lunch!

12:20.032 --> 12:21.783
‐ Yes, of course!

12:21.783 --> 12:23.619
Help yourself to some refreshments

12:23.619 --> 12:26.538
while I introduce the others.

12:26.538 --> 12:29.708
Here, on my left,
we have my right‐hand woman,

12:29.708 --> 12:31.460
Mrs. Kettle.

12:31.460 --> 12:33.545
Her Yorkshire pudding recipe

12:33.545 --> 12:36.882
is to die for. Literally.
‐ Ah!

12:36.882 --> 12:40.177
‐ Next, we have Phoenicia Leatherpants,

12:40.177 --> 12:42.095
a skilled stunt pilot

12:42.095 --> 12:44.723
who's the scourge of the skies.

12:44.723 --> 12:45.474
[grunts]

12:45.474 --> 12:47.142
Baldo Billions,

12:47.142 --> 12:49.853
famously bald American businessman.

12:49.853 --> 12:51.021
His corporation,
[giggling]

12:51.021 --> 12:54.316
CRUELCO, maximizes profits

12:54.316 --> 12:55.734
and pain.

12:55.734 --> 12:58.320
[grunts]
‐ Enough small talk, Doppler!

12:58.320 --> 13:00.489
Why have you brought
us all to this island?

13:00.489 --> 13:04.034
More importantly,
what's the Wi‐Fi password?

13:04.034 --> 13:07.120
‐ It's "Doppler," but the O is a zero.

13:07.120 --> 13:10.666
‐ I have spent years
toiling in solitude.

13:10.666 --> 13:11.834
Hurricane Randy,

13:11.834 --> 13:14.837
Typhoon Mary, Karl the Fog...

13:14.837 --> 13:18.215
Each of them, my precious creation.

13:18.215 --> 13:22.803
But alas, none have had the power to cause
long‐lasting destruction.

13:22.803 --> 13:25.514
That is why I decided to assemble

13:25.514 --> 13:28.517
the best and brightest villains
this wondrous,

13:28.517 --> 13:31.562
thunderous world has ever known!

13:31.562 --> 13:33.772
♪

13:33.772 --> 13:36.066
With our powers combined,

13:36.066 --> 13:39.903
we can conquer the planet
and split the spoils.

13:39.903 --> 13:42.823
Here's what I propose.
[hissing]

13:42.823 --> 13:45.367
Using my ingenious weather technology,

13:45.367 --> 13:49.580
Phoenicia will the seed the clouds
from her aeroplane,

13:49.580 --> 13:51.832
creating the perfect conditions
[sprinkling]

13:51.832 --> 13:54.293
for a massive hailstorm.

13:54.293 --> 13:57.546
Then, Mrs. Kettle shall
activate my patented

13:57.546 --> 14:00.674
Dr. Doppler Doomsday Device.
[squeaking, whistling]

14:00.674 --> 14:02.467
It will produce a powerful storm,

14:02.467 --> 14:05.888
unleashing the largest
hailstones ever recorded.

14:05.888 --> 14:06.972
ALL:
Ooh.

14:06.972 --> 14:10.601
DOPPLER: Once the buildings
of every major city are destroyed,

14:10.601 --> 14:15.147
they will turn to Mr. Billion's
CRUELCO Construction to rebuild,

14:15.147 --> 14:18.692
making us trillionaires
and de facto rulers

14:18.692 --> 14:21.361
over a crushed world.

14:21.361 --> 14:23.280
[panting]

14:23.280 --> 14:25.199
[cheering]

14:25.199 --> 14:28.744
‐ And what, may I ask,
is my contribution in all of this?

14:28.744 --> 14:30.412
‐ You, Mr. Brain,

14:30.412 --> 14:32.289
have the most important task of all.

14:33.040 --> 14:36.877
[sighs]
You will climb
hundreds of meters into the sky,

14:36.877 --> 14:42.591
battling high winds and other
fantastically adverse
weather conditions...

14:42.591 --> 14:45.093
‐ Naturally.
DOPPLER: ...until, finally...

14:45.928 --> 14:48.013
you press the little red button

14:48.013 --> 14:50.641
that opens the giant umbrella over

14:50.641 --> 14:53.143
my beloved Dopplerville.

14:53.894 --> 14:55.062
BRAIN: Wait, that's it?

14:55.062 --> 14:57.314
All I'm supposed to do
is open an umbrella?

14:57.314 --> 14:58.565
‐ But, of course!

14:58.565 --> 15:02.110
You're the only one who's
teensy weensy enough to do it!

15:02.110 --> 15:03.070
[grunting]

15:03.070 --> 15:07.282
Now, who wants
to see if they can outrun a tornado?

15:07.282 --> 15:08.575
[laughs]

15:08.575 --> 15:11.620
[excited chatter]
[splattering]

15:11.620 --> 15:12.621
‐ Ha!

15:13.539 --> 15:14.039
Ah...

15:15.040 --> 15:16.917
BRAIN:
This is ridiculous, Pinky.

15:16.917 --> 15:20.003
I must prove to Dad‐‐ I mean, Dr. Doppler,

15:20.003 --> 15:23.215
that I am worthy of his respect
and utmost confidence.

15:23.215 --> 15:25.509
[rumbling]
Oh!

15:25.509 --> 15:27.052
‐ And how will you do that, Brain?

15:27.052 --> 15:29.304
Oh, please say dance off,
please say dance off.

15:29.304 --> 15:32.432
‐ No, Pinky. I will showcase
my ample talents

15:32.432 --> 15:35.519
and prodigious genius
by neutralizing them.

15:35.519 --> 15:38.772
[laughter]

15:38.772 --> 15:41.483
‐ Say no more, Brain. I'll make
an appointment with the vet.

15:41.483 --> 15:43.193
♪

15:43.193 --> 15:44.987
BRAIN:
You're just in time, Pinky.

15:44.987 --> 15:47.489
With a drop of this tincture
in Baldo's coffee,

15:47.489 --> 15:50.409
his businesses won't be the only
thing shooting raw sewage

15:50.409 --> 15:52.244
into the nation's water supply.

15:52.244 --> 15:54.788
Watch me strike first
in this war of wills.

15:54.788 --> 15:57.040
‐ Ooh! My money's on Will Smith.

15:57.040 --> 15:59.960
Or maybe Will Ferrell?
No, no. Smith to win it all!

15:59.960 --> 16:01.295
[grunts]
‐ Quiet, Pinky.

16:01.295 --> 16:03.255
Both because we have to be stealthy,

16:03.255 --> 16:05.215
and because you're an idiot.

16:05.215 --> 16:07.968
♪

16:07.968 --> 16:10.053
[groans]
[crash]

16:10.053 --> 16:11.889
What in the world?

16:11.889 --> 16:15.475
‐ Oh dear. He's got himself into
quite a pickle, hasn't he?

16:15.475 --> 16:17.936
Ugh! I would kill for a pickle right now.

16:17.936 --> 16:20.898
[gasps] There's one!
‐ [sighs] Come, Pinky.

16:22.357 --> 16:24.109
Things are getting interesting.

16:24.109 --> 16:27.529
It appears, in this game,
I'm not just playing with myself.

16:27.529 --> 16:28.906
‐ [Yakko voice]:
Good night, everybody!

16:28.906 --> 16:31.617
[normal]:
[laugh] I did it! I crossed over!

16:31.617 --> 16:33.619
‐ Quick! There's no time to lose!

16:33.619 --> 16:35.037
♪

16:35.037 --> 16:36.997
Listen carefully, Pinky.

16:36.997 --> 16:39.291
If Mrs. Kettle took down Baldo Billions,

16:39.291 --> 16:41.126
we must put her out of commission

16:41.126 --> 16:43.045
before she does the same to us.

16:43.045 --> 16:47.174
Every day, Mrs. Kettle dusts
the busts in the great hall.

16:47.174 --> 16:49.551
I will make her slip
and fracture her spine

16:49.551 --> 16:53.931
by covering all 3,240 square feet
of hardwood floors

16:53.931 --> 16:56.141
with 1,200 sticks of butter.

16:56.141 --> 16:57.726
‐ Oh, sure.

16:57.726 --> 17:01.188
When we need 1,200 sticks
of butter for your thing...

17:01.522 --> 17:03.440
[clank, whirring]

17:03.815 --> 17:04.816
BOTH:
Ah!

17:04.816 --> 17:06.318
♪

17:06.318 --> 17:09.279
‐ Egad, Brain! She's frozen.

17:09.279 --> 17:11.240
Like Jack Dawson in Titanic.

17:11.240 --> 17:13.367
Or Jack Nicholson in The Shining!

17:13.367 --> 17:16.161
Or Jack Frost in Michael Keaton!

17:16.161 --> 17:18.121
‐ If Mrs. Kettle has been eliminated,

17:18.121 --> 17:20.457
[squeaking, sliding]
that means my adversary must be...

17:20.457 --> 17:22.709
[thud]
Phoenicia, the aviatrix!

17:22.709 --> 17:25.504
Quickly, Pinky,
before she takes to the skies!

17:25.504 --> 17:26.964
[plane rumbling]

17:27.589 --> 17:29.508
Phoenicia! I know it was you!

17:29.508 --> 17:31.301
You may have dispatched the others,

17:31.301 --> 17:33.846
[muffled]:
but you won't get rid of me that easily!

17:33.846 --> 17:37.516
For I am the Brain, the cleverest
and shrewdest mastermind

17:37.516 --> 17:38.684
[muffled]:
in the world!

17:38.684 --> 17:41.603
‐ What!? I can't hear you!

17:41.603 --> 17:44.106
You're gonna have to come closer!

17:44.106 --> 17:45.607
[plane rumbling]

17:45.607 --> 17:47.776
Eh, forget it.

17:47.776 --> 17:50.279
[plane roaring]

17:52.823 --> 17:54.867
[zooming overhead]

17:54.867 --> 17:57.786
♪

17:57.786 --> 18:00.789
[plane sputtering]

18:01.957 --> 18:03.458
[explosion]

18:05.043 --> 18:08.005
‐ Yeah! Egad, Brain, you did it! [laughs]

18:08.005 --> 18:11.216
You showed those rotten
evil‐doers what's what!

18:11.216 --> 18:13.177
‐ But, I didn't, Pinky.

18:13.177 --> 18:15.262
I didn't do anything to anybody.

18:15.262 --> 18:18.223
DOPPLER:
You tried your fuzzy‐scuzzy best,

18:18.223 --> 18:21.476
but there was someone even more devious

18:21.476 --> 18:23.520
and dastardly than you.

18:23.520 --> 18:24.897
Someone who created

18:24.897 --> 18:27.357
a torrent of torment!

18:27.900 --> 18:28.400
[beep]

18:29.568 --> 18:30.569
[clang]
‐ Narf!

18:30.569 --> 18:32.404
‐ Ah! [grunts]
[crash]

18:33.071 --> 18:35.449
[groaning]

18:35.449 --> 18:38.285
[static]
‐ Ooh, you poor thing.

18:38.285 --> 18:40.495
I can't believe you haven't eaten all day.

18:40.495 --> 18:41.622
‐ Narf!

18:41.622 --> 18:42.581
[bang]

18:42.581 --> 18:44.416
‐ Oh my!
[click]

18:44.416 --> 18:46.585
[muffled banging]
[muffled]: Hey! Let me out!

18:46.585 --> 18:48.754
[static]
[glugging]

18:48.754 --> 18:50.005
[shaking]

18:56.970 --> 18:59.139
[boom]

18:59.139 --> 19:00.682
[sizzling]
‐ Narf.

19:01.517 --> 19:04.728
I'm sorry. It was an accident!
I was just hungry!

19:04.728 --> 19:07.356
‐ Hungry for power!

19:07.356 --> 19:09.900
[laughing]

19:09.900 --> 19:13.529
Pinky, you're the most maniacal madman

19:13.529 --> 19:15.697
this side of the Gulf Stream!

19:15.697 --> 19:16.990
I want the two of us

19:16.990 --> 19:19.993
to rule the world together!

19:19.993 --> 19:23.038
‐ This is ridiculous!
Pinky's not a super‐villain.

19:23.038 --> 19:25.249
I'm the brains of the operation!

19:25.249 --> 19:27.167
My name is literally The Brain.

19:27.167 --> 19:29.002
How much more clear‐cut can you get?

19:29.002 --> 19:31.630
‐ Oh! Let's celebrate our new partnership

19:31.630 --> 19:34.174
with some ittle‐biddle vittles, shall we?
[unicycle squeaking]

19:34.174 --> 19:35.175
‐ Pinky, don't you dare!

19:35.175 --> 19:36.593
‐ Oh, I'm sorry, Brain,

19:36.593 --> 19:39.555
but I'm so hungry,
my body is eating itself up,

19:39.555 --> 19:42.683
and I don't taste very good! Ah!
[chomp]

19:42.683 --> 19:44.852
♪

19:47.521 --> 19:49.064
‐ Can you pass a biscuit?

19:49.064 --> 19:51.191
‐ Sure, but it might take me 24 hours.

19:51.191 --> 19:53.861
[laughing]

19:53.861 --> 19:56.530
‐ Oh, Pinky!

19:56.530 --> 19:58.866
You are quite the cut‐up.

19:58.866 --> 20:01.201
Let's toast with some bubbly.

20:01.201 --> 20:02.578
[straining]

20:02.578 --> 20:03.745
[pop]
Oh!

20:03.745 --> 20:06.039
[screaming]
[splash]

20:06.999 --> 20:09.710
[gasps]
‐ Well done, Pinky!

20:09.710 --> 20:11.587
Maybe you are an evil genius.

20:11.587 --> 20:13.463
Was that your plan all along?

20:13.463 --> 20:15.465
‐ What's a... plan?

20:16.175 --> 20:18.051
‐ Right. Well, at any rate,

20:18.051 --> 20:21.471
Dr. Doppler's doomsday device
is now ours for the taking.

20:23.015 --> 20:25.350
[squeak]
[straining]

20:25.350 --> 20:27.895
[both yell]
[spinning]

20:27.895 --> 20:29.938
♪

20:30.981 --> 20:33.984
[pumping, whistle]

20:33.984 --> 20:36.904
[thunder, wind howling]

20:40.073 --> 20:41.325
[screaming]

20:44.036 --> 20:47.414
[maniacal laugh]

20:47.414 --> 20:50.167
It's working! It's working!
[smashing]

20:50.167 --> 20:51.543
PINKY: Ah!
BRAIN: No, wait!

20:51.543 --> 20:53.212
I never put up the umbrella!
[smashing]

20:53.212 --> 20:56.882
[Brain screaming, Pinky laughing]

20:56.882 --> 20:59.426
‐ Fine weather we're having!

21:00.761 --> 21:02.221
[smash]

21:02.221 --> 21:03.764
[wind stops]

21:03.764 --> 21:06.183
♪

21:08.602 --> 21:10.437
‐ It just goes to show you, Brain.

21:10.437 --> 21:13.440
There are no small parts.
Only small packages.

21:13.440 --> 21:17.027
No, wait. Good things come with tiny,
easy to swallow parts.

21:17.027 --> 21:18.070
No, no, that's not it.

21:18.070 --> 21:21.740
‐ Come, Pinky. We must go back to the lab
to prepare for tomorrow night.

21:21.740 --> 21:24.576
‐ Why, Brain? What are we
going to do tomorrow night?

21:24.576 --> 21:26.745
‐ The same thing we do every night, Pinky.

21:26.745 --> 21:27.996
Try to take over the‐‐

21:27.996 --> 21:30.749
[smash, cracking]

21:30.749 --> 21:32.459
world...
[thud]

21:32.918 --> 21:34.795
♪

21:34.795 --> 21:37.297
[panting]

21:39.216 --> 21:41.426
‐ See? I knew Jack and Rose

21:41.426 --> 21:43.220
could have both made it.

21:43.220 --> 21:45.305
♪

21:50.310 --> 21:53.313
♪

22:07.578 --> 22:10.038
‐ Good evening, and welcome to

22:10.038 --> 22:11.999
Math‐terpiece Theater.

22:11.999 --> 22:15.502
Tonight, a community torn apart by greed.

22:15.502 --> 22:17.379
A forbidden love blossoms,

22:17.379 --> 22:19.756
perhaps for the last time.

22:19.756 --> 22:22.759
A meditation on capitalism, if you will.

22:24.887 --> 22:28.015
[coughing, hacking]

22:28.974 --> 22:33.270
A beach ball at the store usually costs
$5.50.

22:33.270 --> 22:38.400
This week, the store sells the beach ball
for $3.25.

22:38.400 --> 22:42.613
How much money will Carlos save
if he buys one beach ball?

22:43.822 --> 22:45.824
♪

22:45.824 --> 22:48.827
[zombie chatter, groaning]

22:50.370 --> 22:51.997
[muffled wailing]

22:52.873 --> 22:55.959
‐ I'm scared!
‐ We're gonna be okay, baby.

22:55.959 --> 22:59.087
They‐they look more worked
up than they really are.

22:59.463 --> 23:00.964
[smash]
[screaming]

23:00.964 --> 23:03.967
[growling]

23:04.259 --> 23:05.928
Carlos! Is that you?

23:07.596 --> 23:08.514
[growls]

23:09.181 --> 23:11.350
‐ Save yourself!

23:11.350 --> 23:12.684
Ah!

23:12.684 --> 23:15.145
[screaming]

23:16.563 --> 23:19.566
[clattering, smashing]

23:20.317 --> 23:21.401
[squeaking]

23:22.402 --> 23:23.237
[growl]

23:23.237 --> 23:24.988
♪

23:24.988 --> 23:27.991
[evil laughter]
[bones cracking]

23:30.160 --> 23:31.662
[crackling]

23:32.037 --> 23:35.207
‐ Carlos, please, get a hold of yourself!

23:35.207 --> 23:36.625
It's not worth it!

23:36.625 --> 23:38.168
You're only saving‐‐

23:38.877 --> 23:41.171
$2.25.

23:41.171 --> 23:43.006
[chalk scraping]

23:43.006 --> 23:46.009
‐ Oh, the humanity.

23:46.718 --> 23:48.595
[glass shattering]
[screaming outside]

23:48.595 --> 23:50.973
NARRATOR:
Next time, on Math‐terpiece Theater...

23:50.973 --> 23:53.976
♪

23:56.812 --> 24:00.107
‐ I need six rubber bands
for each puppet I build,

24:00.107 --> 24:02.484
and I need to build seven puppets.

24:02.484 --> 24:04.903
How many rubber bands will I need?

24:04.903 --> 24:07.489
CREEPY VOICE [muffled]:
Six times seven is 42.

24:07.489 --> 24:08.991
‐ Ah! Who said that?

24:08.991 --> 24:11.285
♪ horror music ♪

24:14.329 --> 24:17.332
♪
